<subSubSection pageId="76" pageNumber="77" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="76.[151,1436,474,571]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,474,499]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The most distinctive feature of the male of 
<taxonomicName box="[768,898,476,499]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Houghia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parmata">
<emphasis box="[768,898,476,499]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">H. parmata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the broad, bright silvery frons (
<figureCitation box="[1282,1366,474,499]" captionStart="FIGURE 39" captionStartId="76.[151,250,1772,1794]" captionTargetBox="[340,1246,623,1750]" captionTargetId="figure@76.[340,1247,623,1750]" captionTargetPageId="76" captionText="FIGURE 39. General morphology of Houghia parmata sp. nov. a. Dorsal habitus. b. Frontal view of head. c. Lateral habitus. d. Posterior view of male terminalia. e. Lateral view of male terminalia. f. Ventral view of sternite 5 + segments 7 + 8." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/287052/files/figure.png" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
Fig. 
<number box="[1335,1366,474,499]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" value="39.0">39</number>
</figureCitation>
b); the frontal vitta is extremely narrow and the lower reclinate orbital setae arise farther back than those of other species, nearer the posterior proclinate fronto-orbital seta, creating a broad silvery frons relatively uninterrupted by setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
