<subSubSection pageId="77" pageNumber="78" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="77.[151,1437,151,1079]" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,946,971]" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Etymology.</emphasis>
From the Latin adjective “ 
<taxonomicName box="[655,750,948,971]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Houghia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parmata">
<emphasis box="[655,750,948,971]" italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">parmata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”, meaning “ 
<emphasis box="[900,1160,946,971]" italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">armed with the parma</emphasis>
”, a small round shield, referring to the broad shiny silver frons with central area uninterrupted by setae or wide frontal vitta, that suggests a shield carried in front of the head.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
